##TOKYO OLYMPICS FACE EPIDEMIC DILEMMA: End of May or meet the deadline for life and death, it is not realistic to postpone the relocation of the Games

REPORTER: Luo Yingying

The Games could be cancelled if the outbreak is not effectively contained by the end of May.

”

Even as the new pneumonia epidemic continues to spread in Japan, local officials, the Tokyo Organizing Committee and the International Olympic Committee have repeatedly stressed that the Tokyo Games will be held on time.

But on February 25th Duecker Pound, a senior official at the International Olympic Committee, told the Associated Press that a new version of the event -- dubbed the Tokyo 2020 Olympics -- could be called off.

Pound said that there is still a three month window to decide the fate of the Tokyo Olympics, and if the local epidemic in Japan can not be effectively contained by the end of May, given the risk of public health incidents, there is a possibility that the Olympics will be cancelled.

At the same time, he argues that options such as postponing or moving the Games are not feasible and that this is not an easy task.

Pound, a former swimmer from Canada, became a member of the International Olympic Committee in 1987, the longest serving member. He has served as chairman of the International Olympic Committee, Chairman of the TV Rights Negotiating Committee, Executive Vice Chairman of the International Olympic Committee, and chairman of the World Anti-Doping Agency.

While the International Olympic Committee has yet to make a clear statement on the future of the Games in Tokyo, Duecker Pound's personal statement does not represent an official comment. But it was seen as a signal from the International Olympic Committee urging the Japanese authorities to fight the epidemic with all their might.

Japan's Olympics Minister Seiko Hashimoto said on February 26 that, "[ we ] have asked the International Olympic Committee and the International Olympic Committee replied, 'This is not an official International Olympic Committee proposition, and this is just an indication that the International Olympic Committee is preparing for the Tokyo Olympics as planned. ' "

Dick Pound

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics are scheduled to be held from July 24 to August 9,2020, and from August 25 to September 6,2020, respectively.

There are still five months to go before the Olympics. Experts including the World Health Organization and the medical community generally believe that it is too early to consider whether to cancel the Tokyo Olympics.

Pound reckons that a three month window to decide the fate of the Tokyo Games in late May, depending on whether the domestic epidemic is under control, is a more appropriate time frame. If the prevention and control effect is not good, when the time comes only two months away from the Olympic Games, may have to be canceled.

As of 20:00 local time on February 25, there had been 861 confirmed cases and three deaths, according to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare and local governments. Of these, 691 were confirmed aboard the Diamond Princess cruise ship in Yokohama.

As many as 17 cases of first-level administrative country subdivision pneumonia have been detected in 47 Japanese cities, and the Japanese government has allocated an emergency 10.3 billion yen to deal with the outbreak.

Affected by the outbreak, many Tokyo Olympic games-related activities have been suspended, including volunteer training and host town summit and so on. In addition, some Olympic venues will be closed to spectators during the test events. Japan's J League has decided to postpone all 94 matches until March 15.

"there are a lot of things that have to be done now, " Duecker Pound said, referring to the Games as a huge sporting event. "We have to strengthen our security, including the food, the Olympic Village and the hotels, and the international media will build their studios there. "

As to whether the Tokyo Olympics will be cancelled, it is not just the International Olympic Committee that is in charge, it needs to consult with the WHO and the UN, consideration should also be given to the interests of other sports organizations, related institutions and even television broadcasters.

Although the situation is unpredictable, Duecker Pound believes that the current signs are that preparations for the Games will continue as planned and that athletes should continue to train as planned.

Recently, in view of the severe situation of the Korean epidemic, the ITTF has decided to postpone the Busan world table tennis match originally scheduled to be held at the end of March, tentatively postponed to June 21 to 28.

At the same time, there have been suggestions that postponing or relocating the Games would also be an option for Tokyo. But from the industry's point of view, that will be hard to achieve.

"In terms of the size of the Olympics, you can't put off the movement of events on that scale, with different league schedules in each country, different events with their own schedules, and the difficulty of co-ordinating television coverage, " Duecker Pound said, the postponement of the Olympic Games is not a simple matter of time.

Especially in the fall, the professional sports calendar is packed with North American Professional Leagues like the NBA and the NFL, European soccer and basketball. Under such circumstances, it will be difficult for the athletes and the national teams to coordinate the schedules of the Olympic Games and the league.

Beyond that, postponing the Olympics is unlikely to satisfy broadcasters.

Since 1988, NBC has owned the rights to broadcast the Summer Games in the United States and has paid for the Games in Tokyo. It is reported that considering the second half of the year there are many professional broadcast plans, they can not accept the Olympic extension of the arrangement.

On February 20th Shaun Bailey, the conservative mayoral candidate for London, said publicly that London would be prepared to host the Games if the new pneumonia outbreak forced the games to be held elsewhere.

His comments were seen as a political ploy for the mayoral election in London in May. London has no plans to take over, a British sports official said, according to Reuters. "This is a candidate for mayor, not a British or London attitude. "

Pound said moving the games to another city as a whole was unlikely, "because there are few places in the world where you can build facilities in such a short period of time. "

At the same time, he disapproves of the idea of spreading the games around the world, as that would not constitute a "one Olympics" , but rather a world championship in individual events.

Japan has already spent about $25 billion to prepare for the Tokyo Olympics. The Tokyo Organizing Committee might not be able to afford a one-year delay in hosting the Games.

"Japan has to ask itself whether this cost bubble can last another year, " Duecker Pound said.

Tokyo sets up Olympic rings

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Currently, the International Olympic Committee has set up an emergency fund, with about $1 billion in reserves, to deal with emergencies. If the Tokyo Olympics were called off, the money would help the International Olympic Committee and sports associations tide over the crisis and keep their organizations afloat.

According to the International Olympic Committee's 2018 financial report, the 20132016 cycle generated $5.7 billion in revenue, 73% of which came from broadcast rights.

In the history of the Olympic Games, there is no precedent for cancellation of the Games because of public health events. It was cancelled only three times during the first World War and the Second World War, tokyo just hosted its first Olympics.

Even though March is a crucial time in the global fight against the epidemic, the Tokyo Organizing Committee insists the Olympic torch relay will continue as usual.

According to the plan, on March 12, the torch-collecting ceremony will be held in Ancient Olympia, Greece, the birthplace of the Olympic Games. The torch will be carried 3,200 kilometers in Greece by 600 torchbearers, and will arrive at the Athens Panathinaiko Stadium on March 19, and Pass it on to a representative of the Tokyo Organizing Committee.

The Olympic torch relay in Japan began on March 26 with a 121-day tour of 47 prefecture of Japan cities from J-village, the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant's staging area.

Whether the torch stand at Tokyo's new national arena will be lit as scheduled at the opening ceremony on July 24 will probably be decided three months from now.
